Perimeter Defense - Email Security > [T1]: DKIM: Email authentication with digital signatures

 

DKIM (Domain Keys Identified Mail) is an email authentication system that allows the receiving mail server to check that an email was indeed sent and authorized by the domain owner. Almost like how SPF works, but instead of validating the IP address of the sending mail server, it validates the sending mail server's digital signature attached to the received email.

 

A digital signature is an electronic way to prove authenticity using public/private key encryption. It works by relying upon two related encryption keys, making one key public -accessible for anyone- and the other private -accessible only to the key owner. Data encrypted with the private key can be decrypted only using the corresponding public key.

 

In our case, the sending mail server -the key owner- creates an electronic signature, encrypts it with its private key, and attaches the signature as a mail header to outgoing emails. The receiving mail server receives the mail, detects the signature attached to the message, and verifies it. It verifies the signature by checking the DNS server of the sending domain for the corresponding public key and determines whether the digital signature is valid or not.

 

A valid signature guarantees the integrity of the received email, meaning the email has not been altered or modified in transit. It also ensures the received email authenticity by validating that an authorized server sent it with a legitimate private key.
 

The public key part of DKIM is published as a DNS TXT record, exactly like SPF.  A single domain can have a single SPF record and multiple DKIM records. Why is that? Because a single domain can have multiple sending mail servers, each has a different private/public key pair. In other words, 1 DKIM record = 1 public key + 1 private key = 1 key pair.  

 

A famous example of the need for multiple DKIM records is when domain owners use an in-house and external email server to send emails (e.g., newsletters). In that case, there will be two sending mail servers -in different locations- for the same domain. To authorize both servers, a single SPF record will include the IP addresses of both servers. But for DKIM, there will be two different records, one for the in-house server and one for the external server -because the encryption keys are different.

Please note that the same key pair can be used on multiple/different servers, but this is not recommended from a security best practices perspective.
 

Since multiple DKIM records can exist for the same domain, the DKIM record includes a mandatory piece of information called 'selector' that domain owners must provide when creating DKIM records. The selector is a string that points to a specific DKIM record in the sending domain DNS server. The selector can be found in the DKIM record published on the DNS server and also in the DKIM header attached to the received email.

 

DKIM records have a standard format of 
 
<selector>._domainkey.<domain>.
 
For example, the DKIM public key for cyberdefenders.org is published at
 
google._domainkey.cyberdefenders.org
 
and can be queried using
 
 dig google._domainkey.cyberdefenders.org TXT | grep DKIM
 

Figure - zoom in

As we can see, the selector string is google. We can also see the public key for that DKIM record. If cyberdefenders.org decides to use an additional mail server to send emails, we will have to create another DKIM key/record and publish the record as any_thing_here._domainkey.cyberdefenders.org

From the recipient's perspective, DKIM verification can have any of the following statuses:

 

Figure - zoom in

 

Status

Explanation

Pass

Valid signature

Fail / HardFail

Invalid signature

Neutral

Authentication could not be completed (e.g., misformatted DKIM header)

None

The email message has not been signed with DKIM

TempError

Transient error (e.g., DNS timeout)

PermError

Permanent error; not likely to go away over time. (e.g., a required header field is missing)

 

Lets look at the following end-to-end example to understand how DKIM works under the hood:

 

Figure - zoom in

 

  1. User omar@sender-company.com sends an email to oways@receiving-company.com using his mail client.
  2. mail.sender-company.com receives the message, signs it using its private key, and adds a DKIM header to the email.
  3. mail.receiving-company.com receives the message and detects the DKIM signature header.
  4. If DKIM verification is active on mail.receiving-company.com, it will approach dns.sender-company.com and fetches the published DKIM public key for domain sending-company.com
  5. mail.receiving-company.com verifies DKIM and determines whether the DKIM signature is valid or not.
  6. If the signature is valid, it will send the mail to the recipient's inbox oways@receiving-company.com. If not, it will deliver it in Junk/Spam.

 

It is worth noting that DKIM signing is optional, and its up to sending-company.com to configure and activate DKIM signing for outgoing messages. If DKIM signing is off, no DKIM headers will be added to outgoing emails. Also, DKIM verification is optional, and its up to receiving-company.com to verify DKIM for inbound messages and take the action it wants.
